Regression and model validation


This week we used linear regression modeling to estimate the effect of attitudes and learning styles on statistics class performance.

  • In a sample of 166 students, global attitude towards statistics predicted how well one performed in the final class exam. Learning style or age were not associated with exam performance.
  • The tested model explained 19% of the variation in exam performance. However, the results should be interpreted with caution, as there was evidence that the assumptions of linear modeling were violated.

Diagnostic plots 

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(my_model2, which=c(1,2,5))


Diagnostic plots are useful for examining whether the assumptions in linear regression modeling have been met. The first plot (residuals vs.fitted) shows that the residuals did not have non-linear patterns. Any non-linear patterns in residuals would violate the assumptions of linear regression modeling. In the Normal Q-Q plot, the points fell along a line in the middle of the graph, but curved off in the extremities. Normal Q-Q plots that exhibit this behavior usually mean the data have more extreme values than would be expected if they truly came from a Normal distribution. In other words, there was evidence that the Points variable violated one of the modeling assumptions. The third plot shows influential outliers in the data. The lower and upper hand corners had no observations, so there did not seem to be outliers that violate the validity of the regression model.

This data approach student achievement in secondary education of two Portuguese schools. The data attributes include student grades, demographic, social and school related features and it was collected by using school reports and questionnaires. The dependent variable in the present report was risky alcohol consumption. First, general level of alcohol consumption was defined as the average of weekday and weekend alcohol consumption (both measured on scale from 1 - very low to 5 - very high). Individual was defined as high-level alcohol user if their averge alcohol consumption was greater than 2.
The main explanatory variables are sex (male, female), quality of family relationships (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent), mothers education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education - 4th grade, 2 - 5th to 9th grade, 3 - secondary education or 4 - higher education), going out with friends (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high).



The hypotheses of the present report are as follows:

  1. Male sex is associatied with higher risk of high alcohol consumption
  2. Better familiy relationships are protective against high alcohol consumption
  3. Mothers low education predicts higher risk of high alcohol consumption
  4. Going out with friends frequently predicts higher risk of high alcohol consumption

The logistic regression model shows that all variables but mothers education had statistically significant relationsips with alcohol consumption (p-value less than 0.05).


Boys, compared to girls, had 2.6 times the odds of being a high risk alcohol user. This result provides support for the first hypothesis of gender differences in high risk alcohol use.


Increase in going out with friends increased the odds of high risk alcohol use. This is also in line with the original hypothesis.


Further, as relationship quality with family decreased, the odds of high risk increased. The result supports the hypothesis that worse family relationships would increase the risk of alcohol consumption.


No support was found for the fourth hypothesis, where mothers education was expected to be associated with alcohol consumption.

The proportion of the so-called false positives was about 5%. The sensitivity of the model (identifying true positive cases) was 13%. The proportion of false negatives was 17%, and specificity of the model (identifying true negatives) was 65%. In sum, the model was not particularly good at identyfying cases of high risk alcohol use. By guessing, one has the probability of 0.15 (?) for identifying high risk users in the present data. Thus, the model performs a bit worse than by pure chance.



Average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data & 10-fold cross-validation 

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

loss_func(class = data$high_use, prob = data$probability)
## [1] 0.2251309
cv <- cv.glm(data = data, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m, K = 10)

cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2356021



The error of 0.24 was found in the 10-fold cross-validation, which is slightly better than the 0.26 error in the DataCamp exercises.

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col=classes, pch=classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 3)


LDA on the training set showed 3 LD dimensions. However, only the first LD seems to work in discriminating cases adequately.

Most variables have rather skewed distributions, except for Expected years of schooling and Percetange of female representatives in parliament. Majority of the countries have relatively low adolescent birth rate. Mean of expected years of education is 13 years, and most of the countries have expected years of eductaion in the range of 11-15 years. Life expectancy is on averge 71 years. The biplot looks quite different in the normalized data. The first PCA did not work very well, since some of the variables had a large variance and some small. The PCA will load on the large variances, which is why there was one component dominating the rest.


There appears to be at least 3 relevant principal components. The first relates to maternal mortality rate and adolescent birth rate. They are closely associated, which makes sense given that in e.g.in developing countries both adolescenct pregnancies and death during childbirth are relatively common, at least in part due to womens position in the society and the lack of access to medical care. Giving birth while very young may also increase the risk of dying during childbirth. This component coud represent something such as state of the womens reproductive health in the country.


The second component includes ratio of women to men in the work force. I would interpret this as the component representing opportunities for women to have economic independence/influence outside the home sphere.


The third component is not quite the same, but rather close to the component with female-to-male ratio in the work force. The proportion of women in the parliament might represent how much women have political power/opportunities to have inluence on politics in the country.


The fourth component includes variables associated with expected years of education and life expectancy. I would interpret this component to be associated with prosperity of the country, educational systems/opportunities, and health care access.
